(Decision
    "NOTA grammar facts that matter for intent records (learned from nota/README.md, not speculation): sequences `[…]` carry homogeneous Vec<T> elements OR heterogeneous tuples — the schema position determines which. Multi-field unnamed tuple structs are FORBIDDEN at the Rust mapping level (line 314 of nota/README.md: 'position cannot be mapped to meaning'). The discipline: lists are homogeneous in practice; heterogeneous positional structures are records `(Type fields…)`. Records require a PascalCase type head; sequences don't. Bare identifiers serve strings; bare `Path` widens the alphabet at Path-typed positions."
    "vectors are of the same type - do those look of the same type to you? … I think you need to learn how nota works and inform the nota skills better"
    "After actually reading nota/README.md instead of speculating. The previous 'nested heterogeneous list' shape was wrong by both grammar (multi-field tuple structs forbidden) and discipline (lists practice-homogeneous; heterogeneous → record)."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19 19:45)

(Decision
    "Restatement shape for intent records: each psyche statement is its own top-level record in the topic file. Same Kind + same/similar summary + new timestamp + new quote each time. No nested vectors, no superfluous wrappers. Append-only (lock-free). Dedup is a query-time operation: the agent reading intent merges records by summary similarity to present 'the current intent' on a topic. Recency = the latest matching record's timestamp."
    "(implied by the psyche's repeated guidance: lists are homogeneous; wrappers must carry variants; properly behaving agent reads the prior before appending — but the structural solution is multiple top-level records, not a nested vector)"
    "Resolving the restatement-handling design: drops the vector idea (NOTA doesn't cleanly carry the nested heterogeneous tuple this would need); each restatement is its own complete record. Preserves lock-free append; preserves verbatim history on the workspace surface (not just in git); recency emerges from the stream."
    Medium
    2026-05-19 19:45)
